### **Exploring Public Sentiment: A Deep Dive into YouTube Comments on Trump’s 2016 vs. 2025 InaugurationS**

### **Introduction**

Donald Trump’s election in 2016 as the 45th President of the United States and his re-election in 2025 mark two critical moments in modern American political history. The 2016 inauguration, known for its "America First" message, was polarizing and sparked debates across political lines. Fast forward to 2025, Trump’s non-consecutive second term has again fueled discussions, reflecting how the political and social climate has evolved over a decade.

YouTube, a widely used platform for public discourse, provides a unique opportunity to analyze how public sentiment has shifted during this period. By examining comments under videos of Trump’s inauguration speeches posted by both right-wing and left-wing channels, we aim to explore how topics of discussion and the associated sentiment have evolved. This research combines techniques like sentiment analysis and topic modeling to uncover patterns and trends in public perception.

### **Research Questions**

How have the dominant topics in YouTube comments under Trump’s inauguration speeches changed between 2016 and 2025?

How does the sentiment associated with these topics vary over time (2016 vs. 2025)?

Do topics and sentiment trends differ between comments on videos posted by left-wing and right-wing channels?

### **Data Source** 

This analysis is based on analyzing the **comments section of four YouTube videos** of Donald Trump’s 2016 and 2025 **inauguration speeches.** Specifically, we use four videos :

**2016 right-wing video:** Posted by a right-leaning channel such as FOX. ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IgRyZvIPFw8](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IgRyZvIPFw8)) 

**2016 left-wing video:** Posted by a left-leaning channel such as ABC news. (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sRBsJNdK1t0)

**2025 right-wing video:** Posted by a right-leaning channel like FoxNews. (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M0YlHWVxcaM)

**2025 left-wing video:** Posted by a left-leaning channel like CNN. (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BNArBr\_J8mA)

These videos were selected to ensure balanced representation of political perspectives and public discourse surrounding the speeches. 

### **Data Collection**

YouTube video comments were collected using  YouTube Data API in Python to extract comment details, including the video title, release date, author, comment text, published time, reply count and like count, saving the data into a file for analysis. For the **dataset size**, approximately 13.000 comments across the four videos were collected, ensuring a robust dataset for the analysis: 

**2016 left-wing video**: 5900 comments

**2016 right-wing video:** 645 comments

**2025 left-wing video:** 3794 comments

**2025 right-wing video:** 3431 comments

Only publicly available comments were collected, ensuring compliance with YouTube’s terms of service and ethical guidelines.

### **Data Analysis \- Methodology**

After importing the dataset and checking for any missing values, which were removed to ensure data quality, the analysis proceeded with the preprocessing step to prepare the textual data for analysis. Below is a detailed description of the steps we implemented. 

### **Preprocessing step** 

### To enhance the cleaning process, we defined a **custom stopword list**. This customization ensures that the processed text is more focused and relevant to our research objectives.Using **regular expressions** (re), we removed any characters that were not words or spaces, such as punctuation and special symbols. This ensures that the text contains only meaningful words for further analysis.

### The text was split into individual sentences using **NLTK's sent\_tokenize function**. For each sentence, we performed **POS tagging**. This step allowed us to assign grammatical roles (nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs) to each word, which was essential for filtering and lemmatization. To reduce words to their root forms, we applied **lemmatization** using NLTK's WordNet lemmatizer.  All words were converted to **lowercase** to maintain consistency and avoid duplication. Using the standard NLTK stopword list, the custom stopwords, and punctuation, we removed irrelevant tokens from the text. This step ensures that only meaningful words remain for analysis. To focus on the most relevant parts of the text, we retained only specific POS tags, so that irrelevant POS tags (like prepositions, determiners) were excluded to refine the text further. After filtering, we reconstructed the text by joining the remaining tokens into a single string. This processed text is now cleaner, more focused, and ready for tasks like topic modeling and sentiment analysis.

**Words frequency distribution** 

After the preprocessing step, we continued the analysis using the **frequency distribution** function which takes all the text from a specific column, combines it and counts how often each word appears. It then creates a **plot** to show the most common words, making it easy to identify trends. 

After that we cleaned the text by removing words that are either used too often, so comments that appear in more than 50% of the comments or are very rare. This helps focus on the most meaningful parts of the text by filtering out irrelevant noise.   
Then the functions **plot\_top\_bigrams**, which finds pairs of words (bigrams) that often appear together and the **plot\_top\_trigrams** function that identifies groups of three words (trigrams) and counts how often they occur. Then to visualize them better, the most common pairs and the most common groups of three words were displayed in **bar charts.** Together, these functions help you explore patterns in text, clean the data and understand common word combinations to prepare the dataset for more advanced analysis like topic modeling or sentiment analysis. **Overview of BERTopic**

Topic models can be useful tools to discover latent topics in collections of documents. Recent studies have shown the feasibility of approach topic modeling as a clustering task. BERTopic is a topic model that extends this process by extracting coherent topic representation through the development of a class-based variation of TF-IDF. More specifically, BERTopic generates document embedding with pre-trained transformer-based language models, clusters these embeddings, and finally, generates topic representations with the class-based TF-IDF procedure. One of BERTopic's key strengths is its ability to account for the context of words and phrases during the analysis, leveraging transformer models to better capture nuanced meanings in textual data. BERTopic generates coherent topics and remains competitive across a variety of benchmarks involving classical models and those that follow the more recent clustering approach of topic modeling.[^1]

**Topic Modeling with BERTopic**

To analyze the YouTube comments across all four datasets, we first merged them into a **single dataset**. This allowed us to **train the BERTopic model** on the entire collection of comments, ensuring that the topics identified would capture patterns and themes relevant to all datasets/videos. After that, we extracted the comments from the merged dataset and used the SentenceTransformer to generate embeddings for the text.

We initialized the BERTopic model with **adjusted parameters** to optimize the topic modeling process. To ensure that each topic contained a sufficient number of comments and remained meaningful, we set a **minimum topic size** of 20, which ensures that each topic contains at least 20 comments, preventing the creation of too many small, less meaningful topics. In addition, initially, the model identified many topics, but, while BERTopic is precise, a high number of topics can make comparative analysis cumbersome. After testing various configurations, we decided to **reduce the topics to 45**, striking a balance between relevance and manageability. This reduction ensured that all topics retained were meaningful and aligned with the goals of our analysis, while still allowing us to compare the results effectively across the four datasets.

#### **Infer topic distributions for the unseen comments in each video**

#### After training the BERTopic model, we applied the trained model to the comments from each **individual video**. This allowed us to analyze the topic probabilities for each video and identify the relative presence of each topic.

#### To determine whether a topic is present in a video, we assume that any topic with a probability score of **less than 0.01** does not exist in that video. This threshold ensures we focus only on topics that have a meaningful presence in the comments. In addition, to make the probabilities comparable and interpretable, we normalized them so that the sum of all topic probabilities for a video equals 1\. This normalization helps us compare the relative importance of topics across videos.

#### Finally, we can interpret the prominence of each topic in the video. Higher probabilities indicate that a specific topic is more prevalent in the comments for that video, while lower probabilities suggest less relevance. This approach allows for a deeper understanding of how the discussions differ between videos. 

**Common topics**  
   
After analyzing the topic probability scores for each of the four videos, we identified five topics that are common across all of them: **Topic 0, Topic 2, Topic 3, Topic 4,** and **Topic 12**. The presence of these shared topics reflects overarching themes that resonate consistently in the public discourse surrounding Trump’s inaugurations in 2017 and 2025\. Below, we provide an interpretation of each topic and why they appear in both years

#### **Topic 0: Patriotism**

#### This topic, centered on words like “Trump,” “president,” “people,” “America,” and “god,” captures themes of patriotism and national pride. Its presence in both the 2017 and 2025 inauguration videos is expected, as inaugurations are inherently tied to the symbolism of leadership, unity and American identity. In both years, discussions under the videos reflect strong expressions of loyalty and support for the country.

#### **Topic 2: Biden and democrats** 

#### Focused on Joe Biden, Kamala Harris and the Democratic Party, this topic includes terms like “Biden,” “Harris,” “Democrat” and “clap.” It likely reflects reactions to Biden’s presidency and the broader Democratic leadership. Its presence in both 2017 and 2025 makes sense due to Biden's significance in both election cycles. In 2016, Biden was completing his term as Vice President under Barack Obama, making him a key figure in discussions around the Democratic Party. In 2024, Biden’s re-election attempt further placed him at the center of political debates, particularly as a rival to Trump, which kept this topic relevant across both years.

#### **Topic 3: Inauguration and speech** 

#### This topic revolves around reflections on inauguration speeches, with keywords like “speech,” “inauguration,” “Obama” and “great.” The focus on speeches is expected for inauguration videos, as they are central moments of presidential ceremonies. Obama’s mention in both years adds continuity to this topic, as he was present at both the inaugurations and remained a prominent political figure in 2025, often referenced for comparisons or as a symbolic contrast to Trump’s presidency.

#### **Topic 4: Support for Trump’s return**  This topic reflects strong support for Trump, featuring words like “president,” “welcome,” “back,” “Trump” and “love.” It highlights public admiration for Trump, both in 2017, when he was elected for the first time, and in 2025, when he returned for a non-consecutive second term. The sentiment of welcoming Trump as a leader and the enthusiasm for his presidency remains a common theme in the comments, uniting discussions from both years.

#### **Topic 12: Economic discussions** This topic focuses on economic debates, with words like “tariff,” “pay,” “revenue,” “money” and “service.” Its recurrence in both 2017 and 2025 videos reflects the consistent importance of economic issues in political discourse. In 2016, Trump’s campaign heavily emphasized renegotiating trade deals and boosting the U.S. economy, which carried into discussions under the videos. By 2025, economic issues, such as inflation, tariffs and trade policies, remained critical points of contention, ensuring this topic’s relevance across both election cycles.

#### **Sentiment Analysis on common topics** 

Sentiment analysis is a valuable tool used to understand the emotional tone of textual data, categorizing it into positive, negative or neutral sentiments. After identifying the common topics across all four videos, we performed sentiment analysis exclusively on these topics to better understand how the tone of discussions varied by video, political alignment (left-leaning or right-leaning channels) and time period (2017 vs. 2025). 

The **Topic 0, Patriotism,** showed **positive** sentiment across all videos,left and right-leaning channels, in both 2016 and 2025\. The comments reflected widespread expressions of pride, unity, and support for the themes of national identity and leadership tied to Trump’s inaugurations.

The sentiment for the **Topic 2,Biden and democrats,** varies significantly.The sentiment for this topic varied between political alignments. Left-leaning channels in both years (2016 and 2025\) expressed **positive** sentiment, likely due to a more favorable view of Joe Biden and the Democratic Party. Conversely, comments from right-leaning channels exhibited a **negative** sentiment, reflecting opposition to Biden and Democratic leadership.

The sentiment for this **Topic 3**,**Inauguration and speech,** was  **positive** across all videos and political alignments. Discussions often focused on the ceremonial aspects of the inauguration speeches and their impact, as well as reflections on Obama’s presence, which added a sense of historical significance to both inaugurations.

The **Topic 4, Support for Trump’s return**, was consistently **positive** across all videos.The comments highlighted admiration and support for Trump’s leadership, both during his first inauguration in 2016 and his return to office in 2025\. It's also important to note that just because the videos were published by left-leaning channels, it doesn’t mean that only anti-Trump viewers comment on them. Supporters of Trump may also engage in the comment sections, even if the platform is typically associated with left-leaning audiences.

The sentiment for the **Topic 12**, **Economic discussions**, revealed more nuanced results. Left-leaning channels in 2016 and 2025 expressed **positive** sentiment, likely tied to optimism about economic policies. However, right-leaning channels were **positive** in 2025 but **negative** in 2016, potentially reflecting dissatisfaction with the economic context at the time of Trump’s first election and greater confidence in his economic promises during his second term. Below there is a summary of the sentiment trends, with the scores, observed for each topic:

**Statistical test** 

We applied the **Friedman test** to analyze whether there were significant differences in sentiment across the four videos for all identified topics. For each topic, the test was conducted using the average sentiment scores from the four videos. The results consistently indicated **no significant differences (p-value \> 0.05)** in sentiment scores across videos for all topics. This suggests that the **sentiment expressed for the topics remains consistent across the different videos**, regardless of the year of the inauguration or the political alignment of the publishing channel.

**Overall sentiment** 

After conducting sentiment analysis on the four videos to get the overall sentiment of the videos, we discovered that the overall sentiment for each video was found to be **positive**. To further investigate and quantify the sentiment differences across the datasets, we plotted the distribution of the sentiment scores for all videos. Observing that the distributions were not normally distributed, we applied the **Kruskal-Wallis H Test**, a non-parametric test that compares medians across multiple groups. 

The results revealed **significant differences** in sentiment scores among the datasets, indicating that the distributions of sentiment scores are not the same across all videos.

To identify which groups were significantly different, we performed a **Dunn’s test** with Bonferroni correction. The results highlighted that the sentiment scores for **left-leaning channels** were **significantly different** from those of **right-leaning channels.** 

These findings suggest that the **political orientation of the YouTube channel strongly influences the sentiment expressed in the comment sections.** 

**Conclusion**

Our analysis shows that the dominant topics in YouTube comments under Trump’s inauguration speeches have evolved between 2016 and 2025\. While some topics, such as patriotism and support for Trump, remained consistent across both years, others were unique to 2025, like the discussions surrounding the California wildfires, reflecting how public discourse adapts to current events. 

Regarding the sentiment associated with these topics, the Friedman test revealed that the sentiment expressed remains consistent across the different videos, regardless of the year of the inauguration or the political alignment of the publishing channel. 

However, when examining the influence of political orientation, we found a significant difference between left-wing and right-wing channels. The political leaning of the YouTube channel strongly affects the sentiment in the comment sections.
